INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (3, 62, 'Object-Oriented Sammy', '', '', '', '2010-02-18 01:32:27', '2010-02-18 01:32:27', 'Quite interesting! I will bookmark this so I can watch the video later after work 8-) <br />What are your thought on it Abby?', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (4, 62, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2010-02-26 04:08:49', '2010-02-26 04:08:49', 'Thanks, Sammy!  Definitely watch the video - it&#39;s got some good points in it, and then I&#39;d be curious to hear your own thoughts on it.<br /><br />I was actually super fortunate to get to see Uncle Bob and James Coplien after doing this post.  Agile Bazaar actually put together a 2 day mini-conference at MIT <i>around</i> this very debate (it got that much attention!).  I blogged on it here: <a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/2008/11/deep-agile-ya-know-like-teenage-sex.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/2008/11/deep-agile-ya-know-like-teenage-sex.html</a><br /><br />And I should say that Cope said he didn&#39;t really think TDD was <i>that</i> evil, and Uncle Bob said <i>yeah, </i>you still need to spend a little time up front (beyond TDD) thinking about the Architecture and just design in general.<br /><br />I actually don&#39;t buy James&#39; arguments #2 and #3: I think that while these arguments might make sense for<i>&lt;span&gt; unit tests&lt;/span&gt; written after</i> the code, I think TDD is not just &quot;writing the unit tests before the code&quot;.  <br /><br />- I think done right, TDD gives you <i>damn good coverage</i> and I don&#39;t think it&#39;s point is to find bugs because, well, there isn&#39;t any CODE yet to HAVE bugs when you write your tests first.  The point is to help you figure out exactly what needs to be done so you write the code without any bugs in the first place.  And then get a really nice safety-net of tests to catch issues if you accidentally break something in the future.<br /><br />- I think TDD is like you figuring out the specs for your class design. sure, you can have bugs in it like any code, but chances are you&#39;ll catch those problems super fast in the red-green-refactor loop.<br /><br />On #1, I think James&#39; concern is that we don&#39;t use agile practices as a substitute for thinking.  And to that, i say <i>Amen, brotha! </i> ;)', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (5, 63, 'joshilewis', '', '', '', '2009-12-02 14:12:22', '2009-12-02 14:12:22', 'I agree with Steve about mocks. Part of the value mocks provide to me, via behaviour-based testing (instead of state-based testing), is it makes system boundaries very explicit; i.e. the unit of code you&#39;re trying to test in isolation has very explicit boundaries (cross-reference your post on unit test purity).<br /><br />This has a lot of value when you&#39;re using layered architectures, such as domain models, repositories etc, or in something like MVC. Mocks allow you to make very explicit what the interaction between a controller and a repository looks like, i.e. the interface. When you&#39;re testing a controller, all you want to assert is that the controller calls a method on the repository (interface), with specific parameters. You don&#39;t care what the repository implementation would return. Mocks allow you to do this.This is design by contract.<br /><br />With regards to design by contract and mocks, most mocking (or isolation) frameworks only let you mock and interface, or virtual methods on a class. This almost forces you to design to an interface, and not an implementation, which is design by contract.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (6, 63, 'joshilewis', '', '', '', '2009-12-02 14:16:05', '2009-12-02 14:16:05', 'With regards to private methods: if changing your private members results in a test breaking, you have violated the principle of encapsulation, which is a fundamental tenet of object orientation, and also broken the abstraction of the object.<br /><br />The meaning of the term &#39;refactor&#39; means to modify the internal workings of a unit, such that its interface is not affected, and it still performs the same. Hence, refactoring a class in the  true sense should break no unit tests.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (7, 67, 'joshilewis', '', '', '', '2009-12-02 14:26:21', '2009-12-02 14:26:21', 'I believe this is the essence of TDD and behaviour driven development (BDD). It gives you a concrete, testable version of &#39;when is it done&#39;. In my opinion, &#39;done&#39; means tested by QA, demonstrated to business stakeholder, merged into &#39;trunk&#39; in your version control system, and ready to be deployed (ideally automatically, through your continuous integration system).<br /><br />I also agree about hard n fast deadlines having a detrimental affect on quality.<br /><br />I&#39;ve discussed some of these ideas in these posts of mine:<br /><a href="http://joshilewis.wordpress.com/2009/11/16/test-driven-development-part-1/" rel="nofollow">TDD - Part 1</a><br /><a href="http://joshilewis.wordpress.com/2009/11/22/tdd-is-a-pull-system/" rel="nofollow">TDD is a pull system</a><br /><a href="http://joshilewis.wordpress.com/2009/11/22/pull-promotes-quality/" rel="nofollow">Pull Promotes Quality</a>', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (8, 69, 'Josh Milane', '', '', '', '2009-12-01 22:12:14', '2009-12-01 22:12:14', 'Don&#39;t you learn how to do it right by doing it wrong?<br /><br />Or at least, I hear some people do... :-D <br /><br />Glad I found you.<br /><br />J', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (11, 80, 'joshilewis', '', '', '', '2009-12-02 10:38:37', '2009-12-02 10:38:37', 'I like the ideas in this post. However, from what I understand, the concepts and techniques you&#39;re describing fit more into the notion of Jidoka - building quality into the line. A poka-yoke is one mechanism used to implement/achieve Jidoka. A poka-yoke is a mechanism for a worker to stop the line when a defect is detected.<br /><br />Also, in my opinion, visual indicators of problems in the line are actually a form of Kanban (visual trigger for action).<br /><br />My thoughts are usually somewhat unformed, so I&#39;m open to debate on anything.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (14, 81, 'Robert Dempsey', '', '', '', '2009-11-30 13:35:25', '2009-11-30 13:35:25', '&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: Times; &quot;&gt;<br />&lt;p&gt;Great post Abby. One item I would add to the list of behaviors we want, is political will. What I mean by that is the willingness to stand up for the team and take the hits as needed. If a team cannot trust their leader to defend them then they will lose all faith. This also allows for the team to try new things without feeling that they&#39;ll be slammed by some manager for &quot;wasting time&quot; when what they are really doing is attempting to improve things or do things better.<br />&lt;/span&gt;', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
