INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (92, 54, 'Frank', '', '', '', '2008-06-03 05:38:00', '2008-06-03 05:38:00', 'What would happen if Rectangle would extend Square instead?\r\n\r\nThe problem here seems to be an inconsistency between the ideal domain model (in which every square is a rectangle but not every rectangle is a square) and the ideal object model (in which Rectangle actually has more functionality than Square - you can set the width but also the height).\r\nSo by having Rectangle extend Square, you could only have a setWidth() method on Square, and add a setHeigth() method on Rectangle.\r\nThis seems like a horrible thing to do, but imagine the classes would instead be called Blob and Blab with Blob needing foo() and Blab needing foo() and foo2(). You wouldn''t think twice about extending Blab from Blob.\r\n\r\nIt would stop working though, when the program would require the shapes to rotate or mirror. Then Square would have more symmetries then Rectangle.\r\n\r\nIn any case, as a matter of principle, the object model should respect the domain model. So the best solution of all, I think, would be to leave the model as it is, with Square extending from Rectangle, but to have both setHeight() and setWidth() "overrule" eachother when Square implements them:\r\n\r\nsetHeight(int height){\r\nthis.height=height;\r\nthis.width=height;\r\n}\r\n\r\nsetWidth(int width){\r\nthis.height=width;\r\nthis.width=width;\r\n}\r\n\r\nAfter all, the whole point of a square is that if you decide on the height you also have decided on the width, and vice versa.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (93, 54, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2008-06-04 18:24:00', '2008-06-04 18:24:00', '<i>What would happen if Rectangle would extend Square instead?</i>\r\n\r\nInteresting. If you had rectangle extend square, would that comply with the LSP? That is, would rectangle be usable through Square''s interface without the need for the user to know the difference?', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (94, 54, 'Frank', '', '', '', '2008-06-09 07:04:00', '2008-06-09 07:04:00', 'It would comply with the LSP, in the sense that all methods of the Square API would have meaning for Rectangle as well. You could have getPerimeterLength(), getDiagonalLength(), getSurface() and so on. Of course Rectangle would have to override these methods'' implementation, but that is not an issue. The only possible problem is when a caller wants to rotate a square, and expects it to have more symmetries then a rectangle actually has.\r\nThe real problem with the idea however is that customers (in this case mathematicians) and developers would be speaking a different language. For one, a rectangle is most definitely not always a square, for the other it is. That is a bad thing because both parties should have a common language when working in a team. The better solution is the second one I described. That one also respects the LSP, does not call for extra methods on Square (just changes the behaviour of the methods already in Rectangle) and respects what the users of the domain model would expect from the object model.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (95, 55, 'Mike', '', '', '', '2008-06-12 12:32:00', '2008-06-12 16:32:00', 'Sorry I accidentally removed my last post, which I only meant to edit. Thanks for sharing this. Your Dad clearly has that experience factor that can be so elusive and important in any new way of doing things, but you also seem to have some of that instinct for seeing things as they are. You don''t seem starstruck by Agile, but you''re not yet ready to discard it, based on the evidence. A bit of idealism combined with the right instinct for what works is a great mix.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (96, 55, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2008-06-13 17:45:00', '2008-06-13 17:45:00', 'Mike, thanks for the note.\r\n\r\nFunny you should use the word starstruck - I''ve been joking that not only did I drink the Scrum kool aid, but I got down and bathed in it. But, it''s true that I''ve never been a big fan of XP, which of course is where a lot agile methods come from. So, I''ve been trying to reconcile that. \r\n\r\nPerhaps I''m just a bit stodgy like the old man "I remember back in the day when we used to program... we''d do it ALONE. None of this PAIR stuff" ;-)', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (97, 60, 'Damon Poole', '', 'http://damonpoole.blogspot.com/', '', '2008-07-03 08:57:00', '2008-07-03 08:57:00', 'Here, here. Though, what do you do if you are not good at being organized? :-)\r\n\r\nHere''s a book that I recommend that is based on the Gallop research:\r\n\r\nFirst, Break All the Rules, Marcus Buckingham and Curt Coffman\r\nFor those that think any person should be able to perform well in any role, this book makes the case that as an employee and as an employer you will get more return on investment by getting people to spend more time doing and improving upon what they are good at and less time doing and trying to improve what they struggle with.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (98, 60, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2008-07-03 10:04:00', '2008-07-03 10:04:00', '<i>what do you do if you are not good at being organized?</i>\r\nThat''s what the ScrumMaster is for ;-)\r\n\r\nIt''s great to see a management book advocating these ideas. I think some of our best managers probably know this stuff intuitively, but it''s awesome to see the theory behind it explained. I just ordered Go Put Your Strengths To Work by Buckingham, just waiting for Mr. UPS man...', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (99, 61, 'Adrian', '', 'http://twitter.com/jexample', '', '2008-08-26 08:03:00', '2008-08-26 08:03:00', 'While I agree that testing individual modules separately, some tests just cannot be separated. This is in particular often the case for different tests cases on the same module. Some things just cannot be done without doing another thing first (just think of add to and remove from a list). The actual problem with your 203 failed tests is not that they are not isolated, but that the framework is not aware of the intrinsic dependencies between them! If only the framework would know about the dependencies, it could tell you instead: 202 ignored test because this single one failed!! My unit tests are pure because they use JExample, which allows you to tell JUnit about tests dependencies using the @Given("testName") annotation, see http://bit.ly/jexample', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (100, 63, 'Anonymous', '', '', '', '2008-07-16 12:58:00', '2008-07-16 12:58:00', 'Testing private methods?\r\n\r\nBad mojo, because I think unit test should be focused on the framework/api... if you change the inner workings, you change them until the unit tests pass, right? That could mean changing the private methods, which is outside the scope of a unit test, if you ask me...', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (101, 63, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2008-07-16 13:29:00', '2008-07-16 13:29:00', 'Thank you! That is my point exactly. \r\n\r\nNow why did I need all those words?', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (102, 63, 'dustmachine', '', 'http://think.bradsbrain.com/', '', '2008-07-18 21:43:00', '2008-07-18 21:43:00', 'But at the same time I''m leaning towards 100% branch coverage in my testing...\r\n\r\nMight it not be possible to have a bug in a private method that doesn''t immediately (or doesn''t always) show up by the public method that uses it?\r\n\r\nDarn, now I''m going to have to take another look at my code to see if I can test enough of the private methods via the public ones...\r\n\r\nGreat post.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (103, 63, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2008-07-20 12:40:00', '2008-07-20 12:40:00', '<i>I''m leaning towards 100% branch coverage in my testing...</i>\r\n\r\nInteresting, how do you go about selecting tests that will give you 100% branch coverage? Do you find that you run into some of the same issues as using mocks or testing private methods directly in that the tests are now dependent on the internals of your code? \r\n\r\nMight it not be possible to have a bug in a private method that doesn''t immediately (or doesn''t always) show up by the public method that uses it?\r\n\r\nI''ve read that if you''re not able to easily validate your private methods through your public methods that this is a code smell and indicates that your code should be re-factored. But I must admit that I don''t understand this reasoning. Would be curious if anyone could elaborate on that...', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (104, 63, 'AbbotOfUnreason', '', 'http://theabbotofunreason.blogspot.com/', '', '2008-08-08 13:00:00', '2008-08-08 13:00:00', 'It seems to me we only care about classes to the extent that they are used by each other (and the system in which they live) -- otherwise a test of the class would be a system test). That is, a class is only interesting because some other class created or did something with it? So by extension, anything that results from a private method was initiated at some level by a public call?\r\n\r\nOr am I on crack?', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (105, 63, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2008-08-08 17:13:00', '2008-08-08 17:13:00', 'hah, your use of the word "interesting" gives you away as a Sixer, you know. ;-)\r\n\r\nI agree re: the private methods should always be instantiated by a public method. I could imagine, however, an instance where the private method abstracts away some yuckness that only has to be dealt with in 1% of cases so that the method can focus on the 99% part, and thus be easier to understand. In such a case, it may indeed be "difficult" to come up with a test case that executes the private method. I''m not sure why, however, this would represent a code smell...? (well, unless it''s that yuckness itself, hmmm)\r\n\r\n(okay, i swear, i''m going to do a post on code smells here soon)', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (106, 63, 'Steve Freeman', '', 'http://www.m3p.co.uk/blog', '', '2009-04-25 06:39:00', '2009-04-25 06:39:00', 'I don''t think you''ve really understood the intention of TDD with Mocks. The point is to design in terms of the roles objects play and how they relate. You shouldn''t be making assertions about the values sucked out of a neighbouring object, only on actions that you''ve asked them to perform for you. More detail at http://www.mockobjects.com/book/tdd-with-objects-intro.html\r\n\r\n...and I just can''t think of a reason to test a private method directly.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (107, 63, 'Abby Fichtner', '', '', '', '2009-04-25 12:56:00', '2009-04-25 12:56:00', 'Steve, this is really interesting. Thank you for posting this. Am I understanding correctly that you''re saying mock objects can actually be used (ala TDD style) to help "tease out" what we want the interfaces of our collaborating objects to even look like? That''s a very cool idea. \r\n\r\nI am sorry that they''re not doing your Pragmatic Mocking Workshop at Agile 2009 - I am really curious on this topic and would like to learn more. Can you recommend any other resources (or perhaps other chapters in your book) that would speak to this further)?', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (108, 63, 'Steve Freeman', '', 'http://www.m3p.co.uk/blog', '', '2009-04-25 17:32:00', '2009-04-25 17:32:00', 'Yes, that''s exactly what we''ve been saying but the message got lost somewhere--which is why we''re going through the pain of writing a book. Take a look at the rest of it and tell us what you think.\r\n\r\nI believe I''ve got a lab of some sort accepted at Agile, so there should be an opportunity there.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (109, 64, 'Anonymous', '', '', '', '2008-07-24 18:20:00', '2008-07-24 18:20:00', 'I can totally relate. I remember telling my Grandmother about various things that I wanted to do with my life and when some of those things happened for me she would make a really big deal about it, always looking me in the eye and saying "hey, you got what you wanted". Now, some years after her passing and getting a lot of stuff that I thought I wanted but didn''t I''ve come to realize part of what she meant is that you better be really confident about what it is that you want, cause there is a good chance you are going to get it. If living life the Agile way is going to help identify what you want with confidence, then huzzah for Agile!', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0);
