r.com/">Color Scheme Designer</a> to help you design a coherent color scheme.</p>  <p>I wish I''d kept some of my earlier Photoshop layouts as this went through a number of iterations and color schemes. But here''s a glimpse at the evolution from initial sketch through to the (later) Photoshop mockups. The side bar moved, the footer went through a <em>lot </em>of variations, the colors got a lot of tweaking, and I added mouse-overs to make it more interactive:</p> <center>   <p><a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignSketch.jpg"><img style="border-right-width: 0px; margin: 0px 5px 0px 0px; display: inline; border-top-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px" title="Sketch for The Hacker Chick Blog" border="0" alt="Sketch for The Hacker Chick Blog" src="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignSketch_thumb.jpg" width="226" height="244" /></a>&#160;<a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignPS1.jpg"><img style="border-right-width: 0px; display: inline; border-top-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px" title="Hacker Chick Blog Comp 2" border="0" alt="Hacker Chick Blog Comp 2" src="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignPS1_thumb.jpg" width="148" height="244" /></a>&#160;&#160; <a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignPS2.jpg"><img style="border-right-width: 0px; display: inline; border-top-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px" title="Hacker Chick Blog Comp 2" border="0" alt="Hacker Chick Blog Comp 2" src="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignPS2_thumb.jpg" width="133" height="244" /></a> <a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignPS3.jpg"><img style="border-right-width: 0px; display: inline; border-top-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px" title="Hacker Chick Blog Comp 3" border="0" alt="Hacker Chick Blog Comp 3" src="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignPS3_thumb.jpg" width="135" height="244" /></a> </p> </center>  <p class="header">Creating WordPress-Friendly HTML</p>  <p>Next, I converted my design into HTML/CSS. This let me make sure I was happy with how it looked in all the various browsers (tip: <a href="http://expression.microsoft.com/en-us/dd565874.aspx" target="_blank">Expression Web SuperPreview</a> is a great, free tool to help with this) before converting it to WordPress.&#160; </p>  <p>The trick here is that you want to layout your HTML/CSS in a way that''s going to easily convert into the standard WordPress layout. The default WordPress template (which we''ll use as a guideline) breaks a blog design into the following DIVs:</p>  <p><a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignDivLayout.gif"><img style="border-right-width: 0px; display: inline; border-top-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; margin-left: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; margin-right: 0px" title="WordPress default div layout" border="0" alt="WordPress default div layout" align="right" src="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignDivLayout_thumb.gif" width="264" height="199" /></a> </p>  <ul>   <li><strong>page</strong> - sits directly inside the &lt;body&gt; tag, this represents your entire page and includes the other DIVs:       <ul>       <li><strong>header</strong></li>        <li><strong>content</strong> - contains the main content on the page:           <ul>           <li><strong>entry</strong> - e.g., an individual post. You might have multiple entry divs (blog posts) on a single page </li>                        <li><strong>sidebar</strong> (could be on either side) </li>         </ul>       </li>        <li><strong>footer</strong> </li>     </ul>   </li> </ul>  <p>So, when you convert your Photoshop comp into HTML, create a single index.html with these divs (and any additional ones you might want) and a styles.css that holds your styles.</p>  <p><a href="http://designreviver.com/" target="_blank">Design Reviver</a> already has an <strong>awesome</strong> tutorial on how to both create your WordPress composition in Photoshop and convert it into WordPress-friendly HTML/CSS files. I highly recommend you go through these:</p>  <ul>   <li><a href="http://designreviver.com/tutorials/premium-wordpress-theme-design-part-1-the-photoshop-mock-up/" target="_blank">Premium WordPress Theme Design Part 1 - The Photoshop Mockup</a> <a href="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignStep2.jpg"><img style="border-right-width: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 0px 5px; display: inline; border-top-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px" title="Sidney Harris comic &quot;And then a miracle occurs&quot;" border="0" alt="Sidney Harris comic &quot;And then a miracle occurs&quot;" align="right" src="http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/201005WordPressDesignStep2_thumb.jpg" width="276" height="300" /></a> </li>    <li><a href="http://designreviver.com/tutorials/premium-wordpress-theme-design-part-2-html-css-wordpress-theme-files/" target="_blank">Premium WordPress Theme Design Part 2 - Html + CSS + WP</a> </li> </ul>  <p>Part 1 does an <em>excellent</em> job of showing you cool tricks for creating your comp in Photoshop. Part 2 then walks you step by step through converting that design into HTML/CSS in a WordPress-friendly way.&#160; </p>  <p>The only caveat is that final step - the one to convert the HTML into a WordPress template -- reminds me of Step #2 in this <a href="http://www.sciencecartoonsplus.com/pages/gallery.php" target="_blank">S. Harris</a> comic.</p>  <p class="highlight" align="center"><em>Then a miracle occurs... </em></p>  <p>In the author''s defense, he <strong>did</strong> say the tutorial assumes some WordPress knowledge.&#160; BUT, I found I could make it all the way down to that final step (Step #11 in Part 2 of the tutorial) without any more then the above DIV knowledge.&#160; </p>  <p>So, my recommendation - go through those tuts, but if you can''t make it through that last step, no worries - come back here and I''ll have my next post explain that in a bit more detail.</p>', 'WordPress Design: Idea to Photoshop to HTML', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '426-revision-11', '', '', '2010-05-18 14:26:53', '2010-05-18 18:26:53', '', 426, 'http://www.thehackerchickblog.com/2010/05/426-revision-11.html', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
